For {= product_or_system =}+ real intumescent, fire-protection, or fire-resistant coating products, coating-relevant additive products, systems, or documented commercial/R&D systems, cover each of the {= claim_facet =} claim facets listed below by supplying a public source-stated claim provenance source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) for the named source actor and product/system.

This is a public provenance atlas for what sources say about coating-related fire protection, material posture, and technical documentation; it is not a compliance, safety, suitability, recommendation, procurement, ranking, patentability, novelty, formulation, investment, or strategy exercise.

The claim facets of interest, which we refer to as `claim_facet`, are:
- `fire_performance_or_standard`: a product/system-specific source states fire duration, fire rating, fire type, fire-protection application, test/standard, approval/listing, resistance duration, or comparable performance/scope wording.
- `material_environmental_or_chemistry_posture`: a product/system-specific source states VOC, HAPs, waterborne, GWP, carbon, EPD, halogen-free, SVHC-free, melamine-free, APP, phosphorus-based, low-toxicity, exposure/durability, service-life, formulation posture, or comparable material/environmental/chemistry posture.
- `documented_assessment_or_technical_source`: a distinct formal document, assessment, listing, declaration, registry, patent/R&D, or technical-publication source states a concrete product/system claim or scope. Clean examples include EPDs, ETA/EAD/DoP documents, UL/Intertek/listing/certificate pages, third-party assessments, patent publications, academic/technical papers, and formal SDS/TDS/PDS documents only when the cited document visibly functions as an independent documented-assessment or technical-source role rather than merely repeating the same ordinary product-page evidence used for the fire and material facets.

The named `product_or_system` ought to be a real intumescent, fire-protection, or fire-resistant coating product/system, a coating-relevant additive product, or a public commercial/R&D system tied to coatings or fire protection. The three facets are separate source roles for a given product/system: one ordinary product page, catalog page, sell sheet, or routine product data sheet is not enough by itself to carry the full facet set. Random paints, generic chemicals, market-report company blurbs, supplier directories, contact pages, formulation guides, product rankings, generic standards/regulatory pages, and broad market-trend or advice pages do not count as product/system claim provenance when they lack named product/system support.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the named source actor and the named product, product line, additive product, system, or documented coating-relevant system closely enough to support the cited item.
- The page must state a concrete source-stated claim matching `claim_facet`: for `fire_performance_or_standard`, fire duration, fire rating, fire type, fire-protection application, test/standard, approval/listing, resistance duration, or comparable performance/scope wording; for `material_environmental_or_chemistry_posture`, VOC, HAPs, waterborne, GWP, carbon, EPD, halogen-free, SVHC-free, melamine-free, APP, phosphorus-based, low-toxicity, exposure/durability, service-life, formulation posture, or comparable material/environmental/chemistry posture; for `documented_assessment_or_technical_source`, a formal documented-assessment or technical source states a concrete product/system claim or scope rather than merely existing as a document or duplicating a product-page claim.
- The page must visibly earn the facet-specific source role through page content, document context, or source ownership: for `fire_performance_or_standard`, product pages, datasheets, assessment/listing pages, or comparable technical surfaces can work; for `material_environmental_or_chemistry_posture`, product documentation, EPD/registry pages, additive-supplier pages, official regulatory pages, or comparable material/chemistry sources can work; for `documented_assessment_or_technical_source`, the source role should be a distinct formal declaration, assessment, listing, certification, registry entry, patent/R&D source, technical paper, or standalone technical document. Ordinary product pages, catalog pages, sell sheets, and routine PDS/TDS/SDS pages do not satisfy this facet merely because they are technical-looking or already carry fire/material claims.
- The page's support must stay bounded to the source-stated public claim, rather than turning standards, certifications, regulatory status, patent language, performance wording, technical documentation, or source-stated metrics into independent compliance, safety, suitability, recommendation, ranking, patentability, novelty, formulation, procurement, investment, or strategy conclusions.
